pd_3_com_1text: If you have nothing to say, then neither do I.
pd_4_com_0text: Perhaps, but this is my humble abode.
pd_5_com_0text: Quite audacious of you to say, but indeed.
pd_8_com_0text: Ha, I see. Well, no worries.
pd_8_com_1text: What brings you to this forest?
pd_9_com_0text: How unfortunate. I'm not particularly fond of shy people.
pd_11_com_0text: Has your shyness worn off now?
pd_12_com_0text: > I'm... not sure. I just wound up here.
pd_13_com_0text: I see you have quite a sharp tongue.
pd_13_com_1text: But yes, I am nosy. So may I ask...
pd_13_com_2text: What brings you to this forest?
pd_14_com_0text: Oh, I apologize if I was rude.
pd_14_com_1text: I shall leave you alone then.
pd_20_com_1text: > Then, I will take my leave.
pd_21_com_1text: > Then, I will take my leave.
pd_23_com_1text: Silence is the default answer I suppose.
pd_25_com_0text: Ha, someone has a sense of humour.
pd_25_com_1text: What can I do for you?
pd_28_com_0text: Ah, you're deep in the forest.
pd_28_com_1text: But I assume you already knew that.
pd_28_com_2text: If you continue East, you'll enter the Tree Village, home of many birdfolk native to this forest.
pd_30_com_1text: > Thank you. I'll be off, then.
pd_33_com_0text: Fair enough. Then, I won't push you.
pd_37_com_0text: The village is directly East of here.
pd_38_com_0text: > Truth is... I don't know my name.
pd_40_com_1text: Could it be, perhaps, that you don't know where your destination is?
pd_41_com_1text: A journey with an unkown destination.
pd_42_com_0text: > I can't seem to remember where I'm supposed to go.
pd_42_com_1text: > I'd rather not talk about it...
pd_43_com_1text: It seems that you are lost in more ways than one.
pd_44_com_1text: Is it that you don't know or that you can't remember?
pd_45_com_0text: > I can't seem to remember... anything.
pd_45_com_1text: > I'd rather not talk about it.
pd_46_com_1text: However, if you ever feel that you want to learn more, come speak to me.
pd_47_com_2text: How long have you been like this?
pd_48_com_1text: Are you feeling better? Have you remembered anything new?
pd_50_com_0text: Oh, we're back to the silent treatment, eh?
pd_51_com_1text: Perhaps a little conversation can help jog your memory?
pd_51_com_2text: Keep an old bird like me company?
pd_54_com_0text: Very good! Now what should we talk about?
pd_55_com_1text: Long ago, before the Tree Village was founded, there was a giant tree that was over 1000 years old.
pd_55_com_2text: Unfortunately, the tree died from a terrible disease about a century ago, no longer in our midst.
pd_55_com_3text: Quite a shame, really. A tree that big would be quite a sight.
pd_56_com_0text: A little bit about myself, hm?
pd_56_com_1text: I've lived in this forest for a long time, longer than you could conceive anyway.
pd_56_com_2text: However, before I lived here, I was raised in the harsh deserts of the Amolan Tribe.
pd_56_com_3text: Maybe someday you'll get to see it, hm?
pd_57_com_0text: You're probably wondering why I live outside the village?
pd_57_com_1text: To tell the truth, I'm a bit of an... outcast.
pd_57_com_2text: The other birds consider me a bit too... eccentric to partake in their lifestyles.
pd_57_com_3text: In fact, if it wasn't for that wretched... ahem.
pd_57_com_4text: Pardon my language. But no matter!
pd_57_com_5text: Living outside the village like this allows me to get to know peculiar strangers such as yourself.
pd_58_com_0text: Did you know? Beyond this forest lies a vast canyon that spreads for miles?
pd_58_com_1text: I've never been, but rumours say that the canyon is so deep that at night...
pd_59_com_0text: > That wretched...? Who were you talking about?
pd_59_com_1text: > You don't seem very happy about it to me.
pd_60_com_0text: There are some things in life we cannot do anything about.
pd_60_com_1text: The current state of things is due to my own negligence, nothing more, nothing less.
pd_61_com_1text: She's an old bird I used to know. We were very close.
pd_61_com_2text: However, as time passed and we grew older, she rose up the ranks to power.
pd_61_com_3text: I suppose you could say that the power hindered her judgment... and our friendship.
pd_63_com_0text: > Well that doesn't sound very good.
pd_63_com_1text: > I guess there's nothing you can do about it.
pd_64_com_2text: Anyway, thank you for your lovely company. I wish you luck with your whole predicament.
pd_64_com_3text: Come back for a chat whenever you find yourself inconvenienced.
pd_65_com_0text: > It might be on the way to wherever I'm headed.
pd_66_com_1text: Sorry but, I should get going now.
pd_67_com_1text: Thanks once again for the company.
pd_68_com_0text: Hm, well I suppose you'll just need to jog your memory.
pd_68_com_1text: Sometimes learning about others can help you learn about yourself.
pd_69_com_0text: I'm not sure how I can help...
pd_69_com_1text: Maybe continue your journey, and perhaps you shall find the answers you seek?
pd_70_com_1text: Unfortunately, things like amensia simply can't be rushed.
pd_70_com_2text: You'll need to take the proper time to regain your memory without overwhelming yourself.
pd_71_com_0text: I'm not sure how I can help...
pd_71_com_1text: Maybe continue your journey, and perhaps you shall find the answers you seek?
pd_73_com_0text: I wish you luck on your journey.
pd_73_com_1text: Remember, feel free to speak to me again if you ever lose your way.
pd_74_com_0text: I wish I could help you more...
pd_74_com_1text: But I believe you will find your way.
pd_74_com_2text: I hope to see you in a better state.
pd_75_com_1text: After all, I'm just an old bird who's lived alone for many years.
pd_75_com_2text: Sorry I could not be of better service.
pd_76_com_1text: That sharp tongue of yours doesn't disappoint.
pd_76_com_2text: Nevertheless, you will have to find your memory on your own.
pd_76_com_3text: With that said, I wish you safe travels.
pd_78_com_0text: Please do not speak to me any further.
